#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/cd_calculator.html:197
msgid "What is a CD (Certificate of Deposit)?"
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/cd_calculator.html:199
msgid ""
"A certificate of deposit (CD) is a savings product offered by banks and "
"credit unions with a fixed interest rate and a fixed term. You agree to "
"leave your money deposited for the term length—from a few months to several "
"years—in exchange for a typically higher rate than regular savings accounts. "
"At maturity, you receive your initial deposit plus the accrued interest."
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/cd_calculator.html:203
msgid "P = principal, r = annual rate, n = compoundings per year, t = years"
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/cd_calculator.html:206
msgid ""
"This calculator shows how much your CD will be worth at maturity, how much "
"interest you earn, and how your balance grows over time. You can compare "
"different term lengths and compounding frequencies."
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/cd_calculator.html:214
msgid "APY (Annual Percentage Yield)"
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/cd_calculator.html:216
msgid ""
"The annual rate of return including compound interest. APY is what banks "
"typically advertise and is higher than the nominal rate when interest "
"compounds more than once per year."
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/cd_calculator.html:220
msgid "Compounding Frequency"
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/cd_calculator.html:222
msgid ""
"How often interest is added to your balance—daily, monthly, quarterly, semi-"
"annually, or annually. More frequent compounding generally means slightly "
"higher effective returns."
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/cd_calculator.html:228
msgid ""
"The length of time you commit to leave your money in the CD. Longer terms "
"often offer higher APYs but your funds are locked until maturity (or you pay "
"an early-withdrawal penalty)."
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/cd_calculator.html:237
