#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/irr_calculator.html:256
msgid "What is IRR?"
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/irr_calculator.html:258
msgid ""
"The Internal Rate of Return (IRR) is the discount rate that makes the Net "
"Present Value (NPV) of all cash flows from a project equal to zero. It "
"represents the expected annual return of the investment. If IRR is greater "
"than your required return (cost of capital), the project is typically "
"considered acceptable."
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/irr_calculator.html:268
msgid "IRR"
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/irr_calculator.html:269
msgid ""
"The annualized return implied by your cash flows. Compare it to your "
"discount rate to decide: Accept (IRR > rate), Reject (IRR < rate), or "
"Indifferent (IRR = rate)."
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/irr_calculator.html:272
msgid "NPV"
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/irr_calculator.html:273
msgid ""
"Net Present Value at your chosen discount rate. Positive NPV means the "
"investment adds value; negative means it destroys value."
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/irr_calculator.html:276
msgid "Payback & Profitability Index"
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/irr_calculator.html:277
msgid ""
"Payback is how many years until cumulative cash flows recover the initial "
"investment. Profitability Index is PV of inflows ÷ initial investment; above "
"1 is good."
msgstr ""

