#: Math_Calculators/templates/math_calculators/confidence_interval_calculator.html:112
msgid "What is a confidence interval?"
msgstr ""

#: Math_Calculators/templates/math_calculators/confidence_interval_calculator.html:115
#, python-format
msgid ""
"A confidence interval is a range of values that is likely to contain the "
"true population parameter with a specified level of confidence. For example, "
"a 95%% confidence interval means we are 95%% confident the true value lies "
"within the interval."
msgstr ""

#: Math_Calculators/templates/math_calculators/confidence_interval_calculator.html:120
msgid "What is the difference between z-interval and t-interval?"
msgstr ""

#: Math_Calculators/templates/math_calculators/confidence_interval_calculator.html:123
msgid ""
"Z-interval is used when the population standard deviation is known. T-"
"interval is used when only the sample standard deviation is known. T-"
"interval accounts for additional uncertainty in the estimate."
msgstr ""

#: Math_Calculators/templates/math_calculators/confidence_interval_calculator.html:128
msgid "What confidence level should I use?"
msgstr ""

#: Math_Calculators/templates/math_calculators/confidence_interval_calculator.html:131
#, python-format
msgid ""
"Common confidence levels are 90%%, 95%%, and 99%%. A 95%% confidence level "
"is most commonly used, meaning we are 95%% confident the true parameter lies "
"within the interval."
msgstr ""

#: Math_Calculators/templates/math_calculators/confidence_interval_calculator.html:136
msgid "What is margin of error?"
msgstr ""

#: Math_Calculators/templates/math_calculators/confidence_interval_calculator.html:139
msgid ""
"Margin of error is half the width of the confidence interval. It represents "
"the maximum amount by which the sample statistic may differ from the true "
"population parameter."
msgstr ""

#: Math_Calculators/templates/math_calculators/confidence_interval_calculator.html:144
msgid "How do I interpret a confidence interval?"
msgstr ""

#: Math_Calculators/templates/math_calculators/confidence_interval_calculator.html:147
#, python-format
msgid ""
"If you have a 95%% confidence interval of [a, b], it means we are 95%% "
"confident that the true population parameter lies between a and b. This does "
"not mean 95%% of the data falls in this range."
msgstr ""

#: Math_Calculators/templates/math_calculators/confidence_interval_calculator.html:170
